04368nam a22007455i 9781501723834DE-B159720190920094934.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190920s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017238347 a10.7591/97815017238342doi  a(DE-B1597)515432  a(OCoLC)1088909957  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aEDU0340102bisacsh04a344.73/07962211 aDwyer, James G., eauthor.10aReligious Schools v. Children's Rights /cJames G. Dwyer. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2001  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the Cornell Paperbacks Edition -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Catholic and Fundamentalist Schooling Today -- t2. The Constitutional Backdrop -- t3. Why Parents' Rights Are Wrong -- t4. Against a Community Right to Educate -- t5. A Right to Equal Treatment -- t6. Justice for Children -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespair over the reported inadequacies of public education leads many people to consider religious schools as an alternative. James G. Dwyer demonstrates, however, that religious schooling is almost completely unregulated and that common pedagogical practices in fundamentalist Christian and Catholic schools may be damaging to children. He presents evidence of excessive restriction of children's basic liberties, stifling of intellectual development, the instilling of dogmatic and intolerant attitudes, as well as the infliction of psychological and emotional harms, including excessive guilt and repression and, especially among girls, diminished self-esteem. Courts, legal and political theorists, and the public typically argue that families and religious communities are entitled to raise their children as they see fit and that the state must remain neutral on religious matters. Dwyer proposes an alternative framework for state policy regarding religious schooling and other child-rearing practices, urging that the focus always be on what is best, from a secular perspective, for the affected children. He argues that the children who attend religious schools have a right to adequate state regulation and oversight of their education. States are obligated to ensure that such schools do not engage in harmful practices and that they provide their students with the training necessary for pursuit of a broad range of careers and for full citizenship in a pluralistic, democratic society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aChurch schoolsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aParent and child (Law)zUnited States. 0aReligious educationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 4aEducation & History Of Education. 4aLegal History & Studies. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / School Safety.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501723834423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501723834.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG